<P>
MORNING REPORT: POP/ROCK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CLAUDIA PUIG and DANIEL CERONE, Arts and entertainment reports from The 
Times, national and international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Las Vegas musicians on strike over the planned decrease of live music in casino 
entertainment in favor of taped performances have picked up the support of Mike 
Greene, president of the National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences. 
Greene is going to Las Vegas today to meet with the musicians picketing five 
major resorts on the Strip and hold a press conference in front of Caesars 
Palace. "Obviously we support recorded music and technology," Greene said 
Thursday. "But more important is the well-being of musicians everywhere." 
CLAUDIA PUIG and DANIEL CERONE 
