<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO COUNTY DIGEST: SAN DIEGO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Vista man pleaded guilty Thursday to a misdemeanor charge related to two 
anti-abortion demonstrations at medical offices last spring. 
</P>
<P>
William R. Lehman Jr. pleaded guilty to one count of violating a federal court 
order that forbids illegal demonstrations by anti-abortion protesters. 
</P>
<P>
In the plea bargain, which was accepted by Municipal Judge Gale E. Kaneshiro, 
Lehman will be placed on probation for three years and receive a suspended 
sentence of 90 days in jail if he follows guidelines similar to those outlined 
in a federal court order issued in March. 
</P>
<P>
Lehman is ordered not to trespass, blockade, or direct others to participate in 
these activities, according Deputy City Atty. Lauri Stock, the prosecutor. 
</P>
<P>
"It should be very clear to Mr. Lehman what he should and should not do," Stock 
said. 
</P>
<P>
Lehman will also be required to complete 180 hours of community service. 
</P>
<P>
In exchange for his plea, the city attorney's office will drop conspiracy 
charges against Lehman, and it will not file a charge of resisting arrest. 
</P>
<P>
"I'm pleased with the result of the negotiations with Mr. Lehman," said Stock, 
who emphasized that Lehman's right to free speech was not being compromised. 
</P>
<P>
Lehman, who was acting as his own attorney, refused to comment on the matter. 
</P>
<P>
The defendant, who in court this week disavowed any affiliation with Operation 
Rescue, was one of eight demonstrators being charged with conspiracy by the 
city. In this case and the others, prosecutors allege that the eight conspired 
April 7 to break laws, one day before a demonstration at a Hillcrest Medical 
Center. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, jury selection began Thursday in Municipal Court for two of Lehman's 
co-defendants charged with conspiracy. Their trial is expected to last about 
one month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<CORRECTION-DATE>
<P>
August 26, 1989, Saturday, San Diego County Edition 
</P>
</CORRECTION-DATE>
<CORRECTION>
<P>
FOR THE RECORD 
</P>
<P>
Because of erroneous information provided by the prosecutor in the case, The 
Times reported incorrectly Friday that anti-abortion demonstrator William R. 
Lehman Jr. pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor violation of a federal court order. 
Lehman pleaded no contest to the charge. 
</P>
</CORRECTION>
