<TEXT>
<P>
Salman Rushdie, the novelist threatened with death by the late Ayatollah 
Ruhollah Khomeini for writing the book "The Satanic Verses," is living apart 
from his American wife, Marianne Wiggins, she announced today through her 
publisher. 
</P>
<P>
Secker and Warburg issued a brief statement saying that Wiggins, herself a 
writer, and the Indian-born Rushdie have been living separately for four weeks. 
</P>
<P>
"Scotland Yard security arrangements for the protection of Mr. Rushdie have 
been reordered since then and Ms. Wiggins does not know where he is," the 
statement said. 
</P>
<P>
The couple had been in hiding since Feb. 14, when Khomeini said Rushdie should 
be killed because "The Satanic Verses" blasphemes Islam. 
